post_text:
Today, September 10, we received confirmation from Fayette Co. Public Health of a positive COVID-19 test of one of our students. This afternoon, we notified staff and parents connected to the Pod of the Kindergarten classroom that was impacted by this exposure. Those that have been exposed or considered in close contact will be quarantined for 14 days. We want to remind the public that we take extraordinary steps to keep our staff and students healthy and happy. The names of those involved will not be shared to protect their privacy. We appreciate everyone’s patience and understanding during these complex times.
As a reminder, if anyone has been exposed or is experiencing symptoms such as shortness of breath, loss of taste or smell, or difficulty breathing, please see your medical provider and please be sure to report them here: https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSdORze4k8zq5BUJ769F45f6-EokIU79e_KGSzgVNCLaUeSepw/viewform?usp=sf_link

post_text: Today we have learned of our first potential COVID-19 positive exposure to one of our classrooms. Although we have taken great measures to keep our staff and students safe, we knew this would inevitably happen. This afternoon, we learned a staff member on our second grade team had been in close contact with someone that tested positive. Those that have been exposed will be quarantined for 14 days. The students that have potentially been exposed, and their families, have been notified and will isolate until we receive further testing information. The names of those involved will not be shared to protect their privacy. We appreciate everyone’s patience and understanding during these complex times. As a reminder, if anyone has been exposed or is experiencing symptoms, please be sure to report them here: https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSdORze4k8zq5BUJ769F45f6-EokIU79e_KGSzgVNCLaUeSepw/viewform?usp=sf_link

post_text:
Today we make history!

This is the 1st day of school for nearly 200 Oelwein School District students starting their learning journey entirely online.
We are extremely proud of the efforts put in to make this day possible from our admin team, O2 teaching staff, district special education staff, and our technology department working to make sure all of the students are able to launch today.
And to our students - your journey will be new, exciting, and challenging, we are wishing you the best of luck.
#HappyHealthAwesome

Oelwein Middle school picture day is scheduled for Monday, August 24. Cohort A students will have their picture taken from 8:10am-10:00am.
We realize it is a Cohort A day, but students from Cohort B can have their picture taken from 10:00am-12:00pm.
Students from Cohort B are asked to enter the building from the west side(the side facing the football stadium) at the double doors for the turf room. Please wear a mask. You will have your temperature taken and will have to hand sanitize upon entry.
If you are unable to attend, there will be a picture day/retake day on Thursday, October 22, which is a Cohort B day. Students have been emailed information on picture day.
The middle school’s online code is 51407YA.

Attention High School Students and Families:
The High School has been open from 8 am to 4 pm the past two weeks to return school property and to retrieve personal items from lockers. We will be extending this opportunity Monday through Wednesday this week. After Wednesday, all remaining items in lockers will be put into "Lost and Found". Students will have an opportunity to go through these items the first week of school in August, after which all items will be donated to Goodwill. Thank you for your cooperation with this.

post_text: Congratulations to this year's "Whatever It Takes" Award winners, as selected by the faculty and staff at Oelwein High School. This award is for students that achieve high excellence in attendance, behavior, citizenship, and academics. Also, overcoming adversity and showing character, drive, and passion are components of this award.

post_text:
If you missed out on grabbing a free Flu Fighter bag stop by Fareway at 4:00 today. We would like to get these to as many households in our community as possible to help slow the spread of COVID-19. Limited to 1 per household/vehicle.

These are part of Mrs. Schmith’s 3rd grade project called Answer For Cancer and were purchased with funds from the McElroy grant.

Each bag includes disinfecting wipes, hand sanitizer and tissues along with an informational flyer.

#wingskindness. #slowthespread

post_text:
HELLO OMS STUDENTS AND PARENTS! MAY 14 IS GOING TO BE AN AWESOME DAY! Each grade level will be hosting an OPTIONAL zoom meeting for students and their teachers to just get together and see one another. This is NOT a LEARNING opportunity but rather a relaxed fun meeting touching base with one another. Soooo....I want to encourage 5th through 8th graders to plan accordingly for May 14th to make time to meet. The zoom links will be sent through email to all students before the meeting times.

5th Grade is zooming from 9-9:45am on May 14th

6th Grade is zooming from 9:45-10:30am on May 14

7th Grade is zooming from 10:30-11:15am on May 14

8th Grade is zooming from 11:15-12pm on May 14

We are SOOOOO EXCITED TO "see" all of you on May 14th!

Make sure to check your emails for zoom and most importantly you will need to download zoom on your computer or phone BEFORE MAY 14th!

The Oelwein Middle School would like to recognize the following students as they have been recognized as Husky PRIDE Award Recipients for the 3rd quarter. The Husky PRIDE award is received by eight students each quarter for representing PRIDE in school. The PRIDE acronym stands for Positive, Responsible, Integrity, Discipline, and Excellence. The following students have been recognized by the OMS staff as showing these values and going above and beyond.

5th: Ava Rechkemmer and Marley Fink
6th: Elzie Fauser and Trevor Beatty
7th: Landyn Yearous and Jenna Helmuth
8th: Dylan Ritter and Alison Steggall

post_text:
Oelwein Community School District Closed until April 30 -
The Oelwein School District has been preparing for an extended closure from the beginning of this pandemic. We will be shifting our focus and resources provided to families to align with the requirements from the Dept. of Education. Although this is terrible news, as our teachers and students are missing each other and their friends, we know it is the right thing to do. We have an obligation as community members and Huskies to do our part to keep the community safe by staying at home and practicing social distancing. It's not what we wanted, but we have a very clear opportunity to preserve human life. New announcements and decisions centered on Prom, Graduation, Spring and Summer Sports, and continued Educational Opportunities will be published early next week.

post_text:
Need internet access for your student and do not have it at home?
We have some ways to help with this! Some of our amazing Oelwein businesses have offered to allow Huskies to park in their lots and access their internet.
We have also found that Medicom and Qwest offer some great options for making internet at home more affordable for lower income families (if you qualify for free or reduced lunch, you may qualify for their discounted internet rates)!
Head over to https://www.oelweinschools.com/help-with-internet-access-for-students/ for more information!

post_text:
Oelwein Students, Family, and Community:
Gov. Reynolds has just announced a recommendation for 4 weeks of closure for Iowa Schools. You will likely see some schools in session tomorrow as they try to plan next steps. We were scheduled to be off tomorrow - so you will not see an official closure announcement yet. Our Leadership Team will be meeting first thing in the morning to plan what a 4 week break will look like for our community. We understand that Food Service and Childcare are major concerns and needs for our families and plan to address those. We have made preliminary plans for support in these areas and will make final announcements on what this will look like tomorrow. We are in uncharted territory. The situation is very fluid and there will be lots of questions to answer in the coming days. We will be posting answers to our COVID-19 page on the District Website. https://www.oelweinschools.com/coronavirus-covid-19-information-from-ocsd/

Stay Safe
Josh Ehn - Superintendent

On March 4th, The Student Leadership team Attended the NEIC Middle School Student Leadership Conference in Waverly. The students from OMS participated in leadership activities and presented to NEIC students on the issues of the vaping epidemic affecting today's youth population. Students came back to Oelwein with a greater understanding of the values leaders use in their roles.
L-R bench: Ashlyn Sauser, MacKenzie Palmer, Amber Dettbarn, Izzy Fauser, Emmah Hoveland, and Jenna Bahe
L-R floor: Sam Macias and Angie Miller

post_text: The OMS had Kindness week from Feb 10 -14th. During the week, OMS students participated in several activities which included a spare change drive to raise money for cancer. The students stood out in front of school in the mornings to collect spare change from parents, walked the halls collecting from students and teachers, and collected money for hat day. The Student Leadership Team ended up collecting $300.00 by the end of the week. The theme of the week was "Kindness is the new cool." Students also showed kindness and received a "kindness is the new cool" bracelet when they were caught doing an act of kindness in the school. The students also participated in a canned food drive as well and handed out kindness candy bars to parents on Friday reminding parents of Parent Teacher Conferences that are coming up on March 9th and 11th. Lastly, the Student Leadership Team did their annual presentation to the middle school. This year's focus was on the issue of the Vaping epidemic that is affecting our youth.

post_text:
Dear Parents / Guardians,

This year’s D.A.R.E. graduation is set for Friday, February 28th, 2020 at 2:00 in the Middle School Auditorium. We hope that you can join us to celebrate and to thank Officer DeJong for teaching these valuable lessons.
Your child is to have a neat and clean appearance and must wear their D.A.R.E. T-shirt which they will receive that day. The first few rows are reserved for the graduates. We remind you to turn off your cell phones during the ceremony. We also ask that you not clap for your individual child, but wait until the end to acknowledge all.
The ceremony will last approximately one hour. Students may go home with their parents. If you wish your child to ride home early with another adult, you must send a note to school. We are responsible for your child, so please check out with Mrs.Smock upon leaving. Students will not be allowed to make phone calls to make arrangements that day. If you cannot attend, your child will complete the day and go home as usual. If you have any questions, please call the school at 283-3015.

6th Grade Core Team

Husky Adventures
January 9 at 11:00 AM ·

Happy, Healthy, Awesome!

Husky Adventures and Husky inc have invited Mike Donahue from Value-Up to speak to students at the middle school and high school on Wednesday, January 15. Value-Up encourages a positive culture in which all people are valued.

Families and the community are invited to hear Mike speak at 5:30 at the high school. A light meal will be served. Interested parties must RSVP the high school by calling 319-283-2731 by 4:00 PM on Tuesday, January 14. Please include the number of attendees to aid us in planning the meal.

If you want to know more about Value-Up, please click the link to their website.

https://value-up.org/

post_text:
Want to come to Husky events, here is some information about our activity passes:
Students: You can attend any of our events using your free activity pass. If you lose it, you do have to pay to replace it, so keep it handy!
Senior Citizens: You can purchase activity passes to come and support our Huskies at all events for only $10 - go to the High School office to get yours!
Staff: You are welcome to attend any and all events - at no cost to you!
Everyone else: You can purchase an annual activity pass at the High School office as follows: Student - $30.00; Adult - $60.00; Family - $100.00
Come out and support our Husky Activities! 🐾🏀🏐🏈🎾🏒🎳🤼👣🏅

CITY Clean and Simple
November 19, 2019 at 3:30 PM ·

Hello! My name is Nicholas Dittmer, and I am currently a senior at Oelwein High School. I am 17 years old and involved in football, basketball, and track along with choir, and the national honor society.
-
I have been interning at CITY for the past month, and so far, my experience at CITY has been awesome! Everyone is always very friendly and willing to help me with anything I need. I am very thankful for the opportunity that CITY has given me through interning with them, and in return, I hope to give them a working student program to help boost their productivity.
-
The most excited I have been so far is when Colin Wetlaufer, CITY's President, gave me a project to do for the company that he was also really excited about.
-
To join Nick and intern at CITY visit: https://www.citycleanandsimple.com/join-our-team/
-
#CITYCleanAndSimple #CleanAndSimple

Community Bank of Oelwein
November 18, 2019 at 9:28 PM ·

Community Bank of Oelwein will be sponsoring a one-time free showing of the SILO film on December 1st at 5 PM at The Grand Theatre in Oelwein. The film, inspired by true events, shows how disaster strikes when a teenager becomes trapped in flowing corn in a grain bin and the rescue mission that follows. We hope to bring awareness of this danger to the farming community. We will have limited spaces.We hope to see you there!

shared_text:
Terry Rex
November 14, 2019 at 2:08 AM ·

I feel very fortunate to be 1 of 10 teachers selected to participate in the Waterloo Black Hawks "Dash 4 Cash" event on Saturday, November 23 during their hockey game with Cedar Rapids. There will be $2500 at stake, and all of the money I collect will go towards purchasing materials for my technology classes. In addition, $3 of every ticket purchased with the following link will automatically go to OMS.

https://waterloo-black-hawks.square.site/product/mr-rex-dash-for-cash/25

Plans are being made to take a bus for students that would like to make the trip to the game, and it will be funded by the 21st Century Grant. Details on how to sign up will be coming soon. The students that sign up and ride the bus will not have to pay to ride the bus or get into the game.

The puck drops at 7:05 PM.

Feel free to share this information with anyone you feel would be interested in joining the fun!

I also am including a movie I made from our reveal of this news today. Thanks to Mr. Post for shooting the video.

post_text: The 5th-grade science students used their new learning about the states of matter to Break into the Breakout EDU box. It's the same concept as an escape room but the students only had 30 minutes to complete their mission. They searched high and low for 4 clues. They used their communication, teamwork and flexibility skills to work as a team to solve the clues in order to successfully open all locks on the box where they found their prize.
